description.narrative:
The intervention aims at the first emergency response to provide protective, inclusive, safe and continued quality education for Covid-19 and conflict affected children in NE Nigeria. The project will achieve improved access for girls/boys to equitable inclusive education and learning opportunities in critical time of interruption of schooling due to crisis and ensure key messages delivered to target beneficiaries on how to protect from Covid-19 and continue quality and relevance of formal and non-formal education through awareness, key advocacy messages, alternative education approaches and back to learning&#58;

Expected results&#58;
1.	Help to prevent the spread and transmission of COVID-19 amongst learners of ECD, basic, junior and senior secondary schools, teachers, parents and SBMCs;
2.	Mitigate/Minimize the impact of school closure due to COVID19 on learning and wellbeing of learners, teachers, parents and SBMC through alternatives solution;
3.	Ensure effective, inclusive and safe return to quality learning for learners, teachers, and SBMC members;
4.	Networking with State and LGA level Government Officials on Covid-19 Response.

This project aims to&#58; 
1) Provide essential supplies like masks, sensitizers, hand gloves, glasses, shoes, soaps, detergents/cleaning materials- education supplies to children and teachers in 100 schools to 20,400 learners (9180 girls and 11,220 boys)
2) Provide incentives for home schooling and capacity building for 624 teachers (220 females and 304 males) and 800 SBMC members/Parents (320 females and 480 males) on Covid, WASH and PSS;
3) Development, printing and distribution of appropriate awareness raising materials (i.e. posters, leaflets, comics), radio messages, SMS/Text messages, social media and SUBEBs/MoEs websites on coronavirus prevention and referrals procedures in the local language to reach to 41,804 individuals (19,380 females and 23,064 males) 
4) Procure educational supplies for 20,400 students for back to learning and work with SUBEBs/MoEs on safe reopening of schools
